</a></div></div></div></div></div></div><div
class="article-body--text "><div
class="ad-gpt-main"><div
class="gpt-tag" id="gpt-ad-vertical-top"></div></div><p><strong>A few days ago,</strong> we looked at the efforts by Governor Scott Walker of Wisconsin -- the latest heartthrob of the Anyone-But-Jeb (!) wing of the Republican party -- to cut $300 million from the public university system of the state he manages on behalf of his various donors. It was one of those conservative scams whereby you preach freedom (removing control of the university from the state itself) in order to destroy that of which you do not approve (handing that control over to a Board of Regents you've packed with cronies). <a
href="http://www.jsonline.com/news/education/scott-walkers-uw-mission-rewrite-could-end-the-wisconsin-idea-b99439020z1-290797681.html" target="_blank">This clever con has not escaped notice in Wisconsin</a>.</p><div
class="pullquote pullquote-C">
<i
class="icon icon-quote"></i><p>First articulated in 1904, the Wisconsin Idea states that the mission  of the UW System is to solve problems and improve people's lives beyond  the classroom. The core principle is that "the boundaries of the  university are the boundaries of the state." Walker hadn't alluded to changing the UW  System's mission during his budget speech Tuesday night; it does not  appear he had ever mentioned it publicly. But in the proposed budget he released  Tuesday, the governor made the UW System's mission to "meet the state's  workforce needs." He also proposed striking language about public  service and improving the human condition, and deleting the phrase:  "Basic to every purpose of the system is the search for truth."</p><div
class="share-button share-button--facebook" data-content-id="34564" data-tracking-id="share-button-facebook" data-url="http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Death_Of_The_Wisconsin_Idea" data-image="http://esq.h-cdn.co/assets/cm/15/07/54d95a4062df1_-_51246238_614-uxodzc-large.jpg">
<a
class="share-button--link share-button--open-window link" title="Share on Facebook" href="//www.facebook.com/v2.0/dialog/feed?app_id=171874009543995&name=First+articulated+in+1904%2C+the+Wisconsin+Idea+states+that+the+mission++of+the+UW+System+is+to+solve+problems+and+improve+people%27s+lives+beyond++the+classroom.+The+core+principle+is+that+%22the+boundaries+of+the++university+are+the+boundaries+of+the+state.%22+Walker+hadn%27t+alluded+to+changing+the+UW++System%27s+mission+during+his+budget+speech+Tuesday+night%3B+it+does+not++appear+he+had+ever+mentioned+it+publicly.+But+in+the+proposed+budget+he+released++Tuesday%2C+the+governor+made+the+UW+System%27s+mission+to+%22meet+the+state%27s++workforce+needs.%22+He+also+proposed+striking+language+about+public++service+and+improving+the+human+condition%2C+and+deleting+the+phrase%3A++%22Basic+to+every+purpose+of+the+system+is+the+search+for+truth.%22&description=&display=popup&link=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Death_Of_The_Wisconsin_Idea&picture=http://esq.h-cdn.co/assets/cm/15/07/54d95a4062df1_-_51246238_614-uxodzc-large.jpg&redirect_uri=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Death_Of_The_Wisconsin_Idea&version=v2.0" target="_blank">
<i
class="share-button--icon icon icon-facebook link-icon"></i>
<span
class="share-button--text link-txt">
Share
<span
class="share-count" data-content-id="34564" data-count="facebook"></span>
</span>
</a></div><div
class="share-button share-button--twitter" data-content-id="34564" data-tracking-id="share-button-twitter" data-url="http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Death_Of_The_Wisconsin_Idea" data-image="http://esq.h-cdn.co/assets/cm/15/07/54d95a4062df1_-_51246238_614-uxodzc-large.jpg">
<a
class="share-button--link share-button--open-window link" title="Share on Twitter" target="_blank" href="//www.twitter.com/share?url=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Death_Of_The_Wisconsin_Idea&text=First+articulated+in+1904%2C+the+Wisconsin+Idea+states+that+the+mission++of+the+UW+System+is+to+solve+p&via=Esquiremag">
<i
class="share-button--icon icon icon-twitter link-icon"></i>
<span
class="share-button--text link-txt">
Tweet
<span
class="share-count" data-content-id="34564" data-count="twitter"></span>
</span>
</a></div></div><div
class="ad-gpt-vertical"><div
class="gpt-tag" id="gpt-ad-vertical-top-mobile"></div></div><p>Of course, when Walker was confronted with this profound change in the stated purpose of his state's universities, he bravely ran away, away, and blamed the people he's trying to whack for the confusion.</p><div
class="pullquote pullquote-C">
<i
class="icon icon-quote"></i><p>Late Wednesday afternoon - long after stories about the governor's  effort lighted up social media and news websites - Walker backed away  when confronted by Milwaukee Journal Sentinel columnist Daniel Bice. He  said the new language was a drafting error and "kind of a nonissue  because that's not a problem with us." Walker implied at an event in Oconomowoc  that UW System officials saw the language and "somehow overlooked" the  changes. "We have no problem" reinserting the Wisconsin Idea, he said.  "Our focus is on creating an authority that gives them full flexibility,  and not on changing the mission." Cross immediately issued a  one-sentence statement thanking the governor for his commitment to the  Wisconsin Idea. However, UW officials did raise  objections before the budget proposal was released, according to Alex  Hummel, associate vice president for communications. Further, at a stop in De Pere earlier in the day, Walker made no mention of any drafting error.</p><div
class="share-button share-button--facebook" data-content-id="34564" data-tracking-id="share-button-facebook" data-url="http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Death_Of_The_Wisconsin_Idea" data-image="http://esq.h-cdn.co/assets/cm/15/07/54d95a4062df1_-_51246238_614-uxodzc-large.jpg">
<a
class="share-button--link share-button--open-window link" title="Share on Facebook" href="//www.facebook.com/v2.0/dialog/feed?app_id=171874009543995&name=Late+Wednesday+afternoon+-+long+after+stories+about+the+governor%27s++effort+lighted+up+social+media+and+news+websites+-+Walker+backed+away++when+confronted+by+Milwaukee+Journal+Sentinel+columnist+Daniel+Bice.+He++said+the+new+language+was+a+drafting+error+and+%22kind+of+a+nonissue++because+that%27s+not+a+problem+with+us.%22+Walker+implied+at+an+event+in+Oconomowoc++that+UW+System+officials+saw+the+language+and+%22somehow+overlooked%22+the++changes.+%22We+have+no+problem%22+reinserting+the+Wisconsin+Idea%2C+he+said.++%22Our+focus+is+on+creating+an+authority+that+gives+them+full+flexibility%2C++and+not+on+changing+the+mission.%22+Cross+immediately+issued+a++one-sentence+statement+thanking+the+governor+for+his+commitment+to+the++Wisconsin+Idea.+However%2C+UW+officials+did+raise++objections+before+the+budget+proposal+was+released%2C+according+to+Alex++Hummel%2C+associate+vice+president+for+communications.+Further%2C+at+a+stop+in+De+Pere+earlier+in+the+day%2C+Walker+made+no+mention+of+any+drafting+error.&description=&display=popup&link=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Death_Of_The_Wisconsin_Idea&picture=http://esq.h-cdn.co/assets/cm/15/07/54d95a4062df1_-_51246238_614-uxodzc-large.jpg&redirect_uri=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Death_Of_The_Wisconsin_Idea&version=v2.0" target="_blank">
