class="share-count" data-content-id="34564" data-count="twitter"></span>
</span>
</a></div></div><div
class="ad-gpt-sharethrough"><div
class="gpt-tag" id="ad-gpt-sharethrough"></div></div><p>In fact, in 1912, while a candidate for president on the Republican ticket, Theodore Roosevelt came to Milwaukee to give a speech. The address was delayed slightly due to Roosevelt's having been shot in the chest on the way to the arena. Once he was there, however, with the bullet still lodged in him, with his doctors and his aides trying to hustle him off to the hospital, Roosevelt concluded his speech by appealing to The Wisconsin Idea as the source of the Progressive movement.</p><div
class="pullquote pullquote-C">
<i
class="icon icon-quote"></i><p>I have a peculiar right to ask that in this great contest you men and  women of Wisconsin shall stand with us. You have taken the lead in  progressive movements here in Wisconsin. You have taught the rest of us  to look to you for inspiration and leadership. Now, friends, you have  made that movement here locally. You will being doing a dreadful  injustice to yourselves; you will be doing a dreadful injustice to the  rest of us throughout the Union, if you fail to stand with us now that  we are making this national movement.</p><div
class="share-button share-button--facebook" data-content-id="34564" data-tracking-id="share-button-facebook" data-url="http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Death_Of_The_Wisconsin_Idea" data-image="http://esq.h-cdn.co/assets/cm/15/07/54d95a4062df1_-_51246238_614-uxodzc-large.jpg">
<a
class="share-button--link share-button--open-window link" title="Share on Facebook" href="//www.facebook.com/v2.0/dialog/feed?app_id=171874009543995&name=I+have+a+peculiar+right+to+ask+that+in+this+great+contest+you+men+and++women+of+Wisconsin+shall+stand+with+us.+You+have+taken+the+lead+in++progressive+movements+here+in+Wisconsin.+You+have+taught+the+rest+of+us++to+look+to+you+for+inspiration+and+leadership.+Now%2C+friends%2C+you+have++made+that+movement+here+locally.+You+will+being+doing+a+dreadful++injustice+to+yourselves%3B+you+will+be+doing+a+dreadful+injustice+to+the++rest+of+us+throughout+the+Union%2C+if+you+fail+to+stand+with+us+now+that++we+are+making+this+national+movement.&description=&display=popup&link=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Death_Of_The_Wisconsin_Idea&picture=http://esq.h-cdn.co/assets/cm/15/07/54d95a4062df1_-_51246238_614-uxodzc-large.jpg&redirect_uri=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Death_Of_The_Wisconsin_Idea&version=v2.0" target="_blank">
<i
class="share-button--icon icon icon-facebook link-icon"></i>
<span
class="share-button--text link-txt">
Share
<span
class="share-count" data-content-id="34564" data-count="facebook"></span>
</span>
</a></div><div
class="share-button share-button--twitter" data-content-id="34564" data-tracking-id="share-button-twitter" data-url="http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Death_Of_The_Wisconsin_Idea" data-image="http://esq.h-cdn.co/assets/cm/15/07/54d95a4062df1_-_51246238_614-uxodzc-large.jpg">
<a
class="share-button--link share-button--open-window link" title="Share on Twitter" target="_blank" href="//www.twitter.com/share?url=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Death_Of_The_Wisconsin_Idea&text=I+have+a+peculiar+right+to+ask+that+in+this+great+contest+you+men+and++women+of+Wisconsin+shall+stand&via=Esquiremag">
<i
class="share-button--icon icon icon-twitter link-icon"></i>
<span
class="share-button--text link-txt">
Tweet
<span
class="share-count" data-content-id="34564" data-count="twitter"></span>
</span>
</a></div></div><p>The forces that Scott Walker represents are the same forces, dressed up in modern drag and operating with the speed and efficiency of modern communication, that Roosevelt and LaFollette and the rest of them saw as threatening to the creative process of self-government back at the turn of the last century. The money power does not need the political entity that is the United States of America except as an organizing infrastructure through which private profits can be insured and increased. The money power does not need its fellow citizens as anything but disposable commodities, and anonymous, interchangeable units, in the mechanism that produces those profits. That is the political and social reality against which The Wisconsin Idea was raised up to combat. It depended vitally on the intellectual ferment of the state's universities, and the products of that ferment as applied in pursuit of a better life for all the state's citizens. The forces for which Scott Walker is only the most recently popular front man are threatened by education, and by knowledge, so they use all the power they have to frighten people about new ways of looking at things, about fresh knowledge, about the process of education itself. They force a kind of mental surrender of the rights of the people to create and sustain a self-governing political commonwealth by convincing those people that anything done together, through the mechanisms of self-government, is a threat to personal, private liberties. You can see it in what Walker's trying to do to the University of Wisconsin, and you can see it to a smaller degree in the way that potential Republican presidential candidates have bamfoozled themselves on the subject of childhood vaccinations. We conquered polio, and smallpox, and measles because we all worked together, and when intelligent people offered us a cure, we made a national movement out of the effort to eradicate these diseases. The government and the universities and the people they produced showed the way, and the country made that cause its own, and we by god eradicated these diseases. We didn't do this as a mindless and fearful herd. We did this because we educated ourselves on what the experts told us was the best way to prevent these diseases. and then we acted on the knowledge that we had gained for ourselves.</p><p>Now, though, a substantial portion of the population has been taught that the worst people in the world to trust are the people who know the most about anything. They have nothing to say to us. We have our good old common sense which, I have learned, grows less sensible as it grows more common. This has been a lesson devised by people whose power is threatened by the act of creating a political commonwealth in which their power  needs must be scrutinized and, if necessary, limited. That is the game Scott Walker is playing. It is far from a new one, and it still can be lost.</p></div><div
class="article-body--share-container">
